<h2>HVAC Systems in New Jersey</h2>
<h3>Climate Considerations</h3>
<p>New Jersey's diverse climate zones require HVAC systems capable of handling both significant cooling loads in summer and substantial heating demands in winter. The state experiences hot, humid summers with temperatures frequently reaching 85-90¬∞F and high humidity levels that can make it feel even warmer. Winters are cold, with temperatures often dropping into the 20s and occasional periods below zero, particularly in northern counties. This dual-season demand means New Jersey homeowners need efficient systems for both heating and cooling.</p>

<p>For cooling systems, SEER ratings of 16-18 are recommended for optimal efficiency in New Jersey's climate. Higher SEER units (20+) may provide additional savings but often have longer payback periods given the state's moderate cooling season. Heat pumps are increasingly popular due to their dual functionality and efficiency, particularly cold-climate heat pumps that maintain efficiency down to -5¬∞F. For areas with existing natural gas infrastructure, high-efficiency gas furnaces (90-95% AFUE) paired with efficient central air conditioning provide reliable, cost-effective climate control.</p>

<p>Humidity control is crucial in New Jersey, making variable-speed systems and proper ductwork design essential for comfort and efficiency. Whole-house dehumidification systems are often recommended to maintain indoor humidity levels between 30-50%, preventing mold growth and improving comfort while reducing cooling loads. Proper sizing is critical ‚Äì oversized systems cycle frequently, failing to remove humidity effectively, while undersized systems struggle to maintain comfort during peak conditions.</p>

