<h2>New Jersey Incentives & Rebates</h2>
<p>New Jersey offers comprehensive incentive programs that significantly reduce the cost of solar and energy-efficient HVAC installations. The federal Investment Tax Credit (ITC) remains the most substantial incentive, providing a 30% tax credit for solar installations through 2032, then stepping down to 26% in 2033 and 22% in 2034. This credit applies to the total system cost, including equipment, installation, and permitting, and can be carried forward if it exceeds your tax liability in the installation year.</p>

<ul>
<li><strong>Federal 30% Solar Tax Credit:</strong> Available for solar panel systems, battery storage, and solar water heating systems. The credit applies to federal income taxes and includes all system components and installation costs. Homeowners can claim the credit the year their system is installed and operational, and unused portions can be rolled over to subsequent tax years.</li>
<li><strong>Solar Renewable Energy Certificate (SREC) Program:</strong> New Jersey's Successor Solar Incentive Program provides long-term revenue streams for solar owners. Systems receive SRECs based on actual production, with current values ranging from \$65-85 per certificate. A typical 7kW system generates 8-10 SRECs annually, providing \$520-850 in additional income for 15 years.</li>
<li><strong>PSE&G Energy Efficiency Programs:</strong> The state's largest utility offers rebates up to \$1,500 for high-efficiency heat pumps, \$800 for ENERGY STAR central air conditioners, and \$400 for smart thermostats. Commercial customers can access custom incentives for larger systems and comprehensive energy audits.</li>
<li><strong>New Jersey Clean Energy Program Rebates:</strong> Provides rebates for efficient HVAC equipment, including up to \$1,200 for geothermal systems, \$500 for ductless mini-splits, and \$300 for high-efficiency furnaces. These rebates stack with utility programs and federal tax credits for maximum savings.</li>
<li><strong>Local Utility Programs:</strong> Atlantic City Electric, JCP&L, and Rockland Electric offer additional rebates for efficient equipment. Many municipalities provide property tax exemptions for solar installations, and some offer expedited permitting processes to reduce soft costs.</li>
</ul>

